description: Borrowed from French cime, cyme (“top, summit”), from the Vulgar Latin *cima, from the Latin cȳma (“young sprout of a cabbage”, “spring shoots of cabbage”), from the Ancient Greek κῦμα (kûma, “anything swollen, such as a wave or billow”; “fetus”, “embryo”, “sprout of a plant”), from κύω (kúō, “I conceive”, “I become pregnant”; in the aorist “I impregnate”). For considerably more information, see cyma, which is an etymological doublet.

entries.meaning: (obsolete, rare) A “head” (of unexpanded leaves, etc.); an opening bud.
(botany) A flattish or convex flower cluster, of the centrifugal or determinate type, on which each axis terminates with a flower which blooms before the flowers below it. Contrast raceme.
examples: The inflorescence is some form of cyme, and the flowers are usually regular.

description: An error for cynne, probably resulting from the overlapping of the two ens in handwriting.
